<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-149-434  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 149 434.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  April 3 1989 v6 n13 p4(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Microsoft to offer advanced font technology with PM. (PresentationManager)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bernard, Diane.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Microsoft Corp plans to add 'font rasterization' technology toOS-2 Presentation Manager in an effort to boost the quality of thegraphical user interface's graphics on low-resolutionmicrocomputers and printers.andP;  Font rasterization will allow usersto scale and rotate fonts on the fly, while maintaining a precisematch between the fonts displayed on-screen and those printed.andO;Microsoft has already met with several developers of font softwareregarding acquisition of a high-level font rasterizer.andP;  Thecompany is expected to chose a vendor by Jun 1989.andP;  Microsoft alsoplans to incorporate font rasterization into its GraphicsProgramming Interface (GPI)-based printer language.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (product development).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   OS/2 Presentation Manager (Graphical user interface) (computerprograms).andO;Topic:     Product DevelopmentFontsGraphics SoftwareEnhancementsGraphical User InterfaceOS-2.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Expanding Graphics Programming Interface (GPI). (table)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Diane BernardandM;Microsoft Corp. plans to add sophisticated font technology to OS/2Presentation Manager in an effort to boost PM graphics quality onlow-resolution PCs and printers, industry sources said last week.andM;The addition of font ''rasterizing'' technology in Presentation Manager willallow users to scale and rotate high-quality fonts on the fly, whilemaintaining a precise match between the fonts displayed on the screen andthose printed, according to industry observers.andM;Microsoft has met with several developers of font software -- includingBitstream Inc., The Company, Agfa Compugraphics and Sun Microsystems Inc. --andO;regarding acquisition of a high-level font rasterizer, which consists ofsource code that allows a screen to display the outline of a font, accordingto sources.andM;The company expects to choose a vendor by June, the sources added.andM;Microsoft also plans to incorporate the rasterizing device into its GraphicsProgramming Interface-based printer language, according to the sources.andM;Such an inclusion is necessary because a printer controller for PM graphicsrequires the same font-outline capabilities in the printer as it does in theoperating system, according to Jonathan Seybold, editor of the Seybold Reporton Desktop Publishing, in Malibu, Calif.andM;Microsoft is ''working on enhancing the output capability of PresentationManager, and increasing PM font capabilities is a big part of that effort,''according to Marty Taucker, a spokesman for Microsoft in Redmond, Wash.andM;Taucker refused to give details or say which technology Microsoft will use.andM;According to sources, Microsoft intends to add the font rasterizer to theexisting PM as a standard feature.andM;Instead of loading a separate software program to create outline fonts, userswill automatically have access to the capability after booting their systems,according to the sources.andM;The fonts currently used in Presentation Manager have been criticized by someobservers for their lack of clarity in low-resolution environments.andM;''Microsoft needs to solve problems like cracked letters and irregularspacing that occur when displaying and scaling fonts at low PC-levelresolutions,'' said a source from a font-software firm who wished to remainunidentified.andM;Each of the font developers being considered by Microsoft would bring uniquefeatures to Presentation Manager, observers said.andM;Sun's Folio typeface technology, for example, allows users to render fontsusing a very small portion of the screen.andM;''Sun technology gets fonts down to the smallest possible space on thescreen,'' said a font-software official who requested anonymity.andM;Bitstream's Speed-O and The Company's Nimbus-Q rasterizers operate at muchhigher speeds than Sun's offering, according to the official.andM;While speed and screen size are important considerations, the ability togenerate a typeface library will also be an essential factor in Microsoft'schoice of a font vendor, according to sources.andM;''Microsoft wants to give Presentation Manager users everything Adobe[Systems Inc.] gives PostScript users, from standard scalable fonts to a widechoice of typefaces,'' said an employee from one font company that met withMicrosoft.andO;</TEXT></DOC>